Hands-On: the Sample Average

Introduction

In this MATLAB live script, we briefly introduce the sample average and median for readers less familiar with statistics. We highlight those aspects that will be important to interpret the results from the system identification point of view. We also use the opportunity to introduce estimators, a fundamental concept in system identification (please, refer to the L7 part of the class material for an introduction to the propertiies and definitions regarding both the estimation and the prediction problem).

The Sample Mean as an Estimator of the Mean Value of a Distribution

Consider the random variable with mean value Then the sample mean of N observations of X is an estimator of the mean value μ. The indicates that it is an estimated value.
An estimator is a function that calculates an estimate for a parameter θ that characterizes the observed variables, starting from the observations . In this case , and the estimator .
The estimator is a random variable: As the observations are samples of the random variable X, the estimate that is a function of these samples is a sample of a random variable too. We will use statistical tools to characterize . Below we discuss in more detail some aspects (expected value, variance, distribution) of the random behavior of .
Multiple choices for the estimator function are possible. The system identification theory offers a systematic framework to understand better how to select the estimator that is best suited to solve a given problem, and to understand/study its stochastic properties. Here we will illustrate some aspects on the example of estimating the mean value of a distribution.

NAll=2.^(1:16); % let's create a few data sets: each dataset contains 2ˆN data
R = 10; % how many repetitions?
 
 
% ---------------------
X = randn(max(NAll),R); % generate the random data as Gaussian r.v. with
% 0 as the mean value, and 1 as the variance value
% ---------------------
 
XmeanAll = zeros(numel(NAll), R); % preallocate memory in the workspace
% filling the array with zeros
% --- calculate the mean values ---
for k = numel(NAll):-1:1
XmeanAll(k,:) = mean(X(1:NAll(k),:),1);
end
% --- calculate the mean values ---
 
 
figure('Units','normalized','Position',[0.1, 0.1, 0.85, 0.75])
% --- Let's show what a single realisation looks like ---
hax1 = subplot(1,2,1);
semilogx(NAll,XmeanAll(:,1),'.-b',NAll,2./NAll.^0.5,'r',NAll,-2./NAll.^0.5,'r')
xlabel('N')
title({'Sample Mean','1 realization'})
legend({'$\hat{\mu}$','$2\sigma_\mu$'},'Interpreter','latex')
set(hax1, 'Fontsize', 14)
% --- Let's show the 10 realizations ---
hax2 = subplot(1,2,2);
semilogx(NAll,XmeanAll(:,1:10),'.-b',NAll,2./NAll.^0.5,'r',NAll,-2./NAll.^0.5,'r')
xlabel('N')
title({'Sample Mean','10 realizations'})
set(hax2, 'Fontsize', 14)

Confidence interval

The confidence interval gives an idea about the reliability of a result with respect to random variations, it does not include the impact of systematic errors (bias errors). These should be studied through a theoretical analysis, or eliminated by making a calibration measurement. Since (see Exercise 1), we have that the bias of the sample mean is zero so that we can focus completely on the random variations.
The uncertainty interval of is the interval with the value a selected such that
.
Here, α is the probability that the true value μ lays outside the considered interval. The width of the interval is set by the choice of a and the desired value of α. For example, for a normal distribution and , we have that , resulting in the 95% uncertainty interval. Observe that the relation between a and α depends on the distribution of . This distribution will be studied in the next section. Other commonly used values of a are , , , and .
The confidence interval is centered around that varies from one realization to the other, so also the uncertainty interval will vary. However, by definition we know that there is a probability of that the true value μ is in the interval.
Remarks
  • In practice, the value σ is unknown and has to be estimated as well. This will be discussed in the Hands-On The Sample Variance.
  • The distribution of the estimate strongly influences the choice of a, especially from small values of N, for example . In the next section it will be shown that for a growing value of N the distribution of becomes asymptotically normal, so that in practice the table of the normal distribution can be used in most cases.

N =76; % number of samples
R =50; % number of realization
a =1; % number of standard deviations
 
 
X = randn(N,R); % let's generate the r.values
 
XmeanAll = mean(X,1); % the running mean
 
 
figure('Units','normalized','Position',[0.1, 0.1, 0.85, 0.75])
 
sigmaMean=1/sqrt(N); % the std. dev. the estimated mean value
errorbar(XmeanAll,a*sigmaMean*ones(size(XmeanAll)),'ob','linewidth',1)
hold on
plot((1:R),zeros(1,R),'r')

xlabel('Realization number')
title(['Sample mean with ',num2str(a),' sigma interval'])
set(gca, 'Fontsize', 14);

Distribution of the sample mean: a first impression (Hint: Not for One New to Statistics)

The sample mean of a random variable X is a random variable as well. It has a distribution and pdf (assuming that the derivative of exists) that depend on the original distribution of X. In the next illustration, we show that , converge to a normal distribution for , independently of the original distribution . This follows directly from the central limit theorem that applies to all distributions with a finite variance.
We start from two different distributions : a normal distribution, and a uniform distribution. All have a zero mean () and a unit variance (). For the three situations, is calculated for and this for realizations. For the normal and uniform distribution, the estimated pdf of is plotted. For the binary distribution the probability mass function (pmf) is shown, the pdf does not exist in this case (why?). From this plot the following observations can be made:
  • Normal distribution : . The normal distribution for follows from the property that a linear combination of normally distributed random variables is also normally distributed. The mean value and variance are calculated in Exercises 1 and 2.
  • Uniform distribution : Replacing the normal distribtuion by the uniform distribution (check that X has a zero mean and a unit variance) does not change the mean and variance of (see the solutions of Exercises 1 and 2): and , but the distribution changes. 1) The pdf of the sum of two random variables is given by the convolution The convolution of two rectangular functions is a triangular with double width. 2) : This can be considered as , where the two terms in the sum have both a triangular distribution. The convolution of the two triangular functions starts to look like a normal distribution. The similarity is even better for .
  • Repeat the simulation a few times and observe the (small) random fluctuations in the estimated results. For lower values of R, these variations would become larger.
 
% ------ distribution sample mean ------
NAll=[2 4 16];nAll=length(NAll);
R=10000;
 
 
% --- plot starting distributions ---
c=linspace(-3,3,1001); % centers for the pdf calculations
 
XNorm0pdf=normpdf(c); % normal distribution
 
XUnif0pdf=zeros(size(c));XUnif0pdf(abs(c)<=sqrt(3))=0.5/sqrt(3); % Uniform distribution
 
 
Center=linspace(-3,3,101);d=Center(2)-Center(1); % centers for the histogram
 
XNorm = randn(max(NAll),R);
XUnif = (rand(max(NAll),R)-0.5)*sqrt(12); % generate uniform distribution with unit variance
 
for k=length(NAll):-1:1
XmeanAllNorm(k,:)=mean(XNorm(1:NAll(k),:),1);
XmeanAllUnif(k,:)=mean(XUnif(1:NAll(k),:),1);
end
 
figure('Units','normalized','Position',[0.1, 0.1, 0.85, 0.75])
 
% theoretical distributions
subplot(nAll+1,2,1),
plot(c,XNorm0pdf),title('Normal'),axis([-3,3,0,0.55]),ylabel('pdf')
subplot(nAll+1,2,2),
plot(c,XUnif0pdf),axis([-3,3,0,0.55]),title('Uniform'),ylabel('pdf')
 
 
% sample distributions of the sample mean
for k=1:nAll
[n]=hist(XmeanAllNorm(k,:),Center);pdfEst=n/R/d;
subplot(nAll+1,2,2*k+1);
plot(Center,pdfEst),axis([-3,3,0,2]);
ylabel('pdf')
 
[n]=hist(XmeanAllUnif(k,:),Center);pdfEst=n/R/d;
subplot(nAll+1,2,2*k+2);
plot(Center,pdfEst)
axis([-3,3,0,2]);
title(['Sample mean ',num2str(NAll(k)),' samples']);
ylabel('pdf')
end

Definition of the median

The median m of is defined as and , it is the value that splits the probability mass in two equal parts.
For example, the median of is . Observe that in this case and which is in agreement with the definition. For a discrete set with an odd number of samples N, the median is , with the samples arranged in increasing order such that . For a discrete set with an even number of samples N, the median is the interval . In that case, the center value of the interval is often selected as the median .

The sample median as an estimate for the mean

For a normal distribution , the median is . This shows that the sample median with drawn from the normal distribution is also an estimate for its mean value μ.
This is true for all symmetric distributions. For a symmetric distribution, the probability mass is symmetrically distributed around its mean value (for example ) and hence the median equals the mean .

The sample mean and sample median of a normal distribution

This raises the question which is the best estimator for the mean value μ of a random variable . Is it the sample mean or the sample median ? In the next figure, the result of a simulation for is shown.
N=10;
R=100;
 
X=randn(N,R); % generate R realizations of length N
Xmean = mean(X,1);
Xmedian = median(X,1);
 
figure('Units','normalized','Position',[0.1, 0.1, 0.85, 0.75])
 
plot(1:R,Xmean,'+',1:R,Xmedian,'o', 'MarkerSize', 14, 'LineWidth', 1.5)
title('Sample Mean and Median Normal distribution')
xlabel('Realization')
axis([0 R -2 2])
legend(['$\sigma_{mean} = $',num2str(std(Xmean))],...
['$\sigma_{median} = $',num2str(std(Xmedian))],'interpreter','latex')
set(gca, 'Fontsize', 14)
This suggests that has a smaller standard deviation than and hence is to be preferred. However, the full answer depends on the nature of the distribution .

What You Learned

We introduced the sample mean and studied its use as an estimator for the mean value of a random variable. We put the results also in a system identification setting.
The sample mean calculated from a finite number of samples is also a random variable.
The sample mean is an unbiased estimate of the mean μ. Its expected value equals the true value , or, in system identification terms, .
The standard deviation , it drops to zero for a growing number of samples. If the number of samples is multiplied with 100, the standard deviation is reduced with a factor 10. This is a rather slow reduction, the cost to make longer experiments can grow fast.
The sample mean is asymptotically normally distributed, independent of the distribution of the 'disturbing' noise e. The convergence for the tails of the distribution is slower than that of the 'bulk' of the distribution.
This information can be used to construct a confidence interval around that contains μ with a user defined probability.
The median is an alternative estimator to estimate the mean of a symmetric distribution. This shows that an estimator is not unique, multiple possibilities exist.
The median is less sensitive to outliers, but for the normal distribution it has a larger uncertainty than the sample mean.
